# -*- encoding: utf-8 -*-
# Arc: UnionKingdom | Scene: UnionKingdom2
# Source: C:\Program Files (x86)\Steam\steamapps\common\The Survival of Sarah Rose\game\script.rpy

translate ru strings:

    old "With the celebrations behind her, Sarah had returned to business as usual."
    new "With the celebrations behind her, Sarah had returned to business as usual."

    old "The council meetings in the days after had proven to be little more than the usual busy-work."
    new "The council meetings in the days after had proven to be little more than the usual busy-work."

    old "These men hail from the Northern province, where they worked as merchants."
    new "These men hail from the Northern province, where they worked as merchants."

    old "Worked?"
    new "Worked?"

    old "She was overseeing the weekly court session where small disputes were brought before the Crown to be resolved."
    new "She was overseeing the weekly court session where small disputes were brought before the Crown to be resolved."

    old "Most of these matters were small. Trivial. And their petitioners equally of small stature."
    new "Most of these matters were small. Trivial. And their petitioners equally of small stature."

    old "Often they had to wait weeks, sometimes months, just to have their cases heard."
    new "Often they had to wait weeks, sometimes months, just to have their cases heard."

    old "Aah yes, there is a matter of their cargo."
    new "Aah yes, there is a matter of their cargo."

    old "Sarah struggled to remain focussed on the boring dredge of cases."
    new "Sarah struggled to remain focussed on the boring dredge of cases."

    old "Her mind was continually occupied with only one consideration...Lily."
    new "Her mind was continually occupied with only one consideration...Lily."

    old "Lily had been called away on business the day after, and they had hardly spoken since."
    new "Lily had been called away on business the day after, and they had hardly spoken since."

    old "But she was set to return soon, and Sarah felt her own heart beat faster with anticipation or fear."
    new "But she was set to return soon, and Sarah felt her own heart beat faster with anticipation or fear."

    old "With your permission, your Grace, allow me to explain."
    new "With your permission, your Grace, allow me to explain."

    old "Sarah nodded and motioned for the man to continue."
    new "Sarah nodded and motioned for the man to continue."

    old "We were transporting a series of goods from the Northern provinces down to the capital."
    new "We were transporting a series of goods from the Northern provinces down to the capital."

    old "We took these goods on assignment from Lord Greytower."
    new "We took these goods on assignment from Lord Greytower."

    old "Lord Greytower was a relatively unimportant head of a family tasking with overseeing one of the smaller provinces in the North."
    new "Lord Greytower was a relatively unimportant head of a family tasking with overseeing one of the smaller provinces in the North."

    old "Its small size and distant location made it uninteresting to most merchants."
    new "Its small size and distant location made it uninteresting to most merchants."

    old "Additionally, the cold ground made farming difficult in some parts and impossible in most."
    new "Additionally, the cold ground made farming difficult in some parts and impossible in most."

    old "Finally, too far away from the mountains, the province could not even boast any real industry."
    new "Finally, too far away from the mountains, the province could not even boast any real industry."

    old "It was poor, and perhaps, that was its only attraction. Cheap land and cheap homes for those too poor to manage anywhere else."
    new "It was poor, and perhaps, that was its only attraction. Cheap land and cheap homes for those too poor to manage anywhere else."

    old "You took the goods on assignment from Lord Greytower? Is there a contract speaking to this?"
    new "You took the goods on assignment from Lord Greytower? Is there a contract speaking to this?"

    old "The merchant nodded."
    new "The merchant nodded."

    old "We gave the contract to your Spymaster. It states clearly that we only accept transporting the goods, we don't accept to carry any risk!"
    new "We gave the contract to your Spymaster. It states clearly that we only accept transporting the goods, we don't accept to carry any risk!"

    old "Sarah looked at Kravel, who nodded, seeming to confirm what the man said."
    new "Sarah looked at Kravel, who nodded, seeming to confirm what the man said."

    old "So...what happened, concretely?"
    new "So...what happened, concretely?"

    old "We took on the cargo and headed towards the capital."
    new "We took on the cargo and headed towards the capital."

    old "But no more than a twenty-miles from where we began, a gang of thieves robbed us and took everything!"
    new "But no more than a twenty-miles from where we began, a gang of thieves robbed us and took everything!"

    old "Sarah frowned as she listened."
    new "Sarah frowned as she listened."

    old "Rosanna was thriving, but even in good times, there were men who made their ways through violence and crime."
    new "Rosanna was thriving, but even in good times, there were men who made their ways through violence and crime."

    old "So the cargo was stolen?"
    new "So the cargo was stolen?"

    old "The cargo was stolen, but Lord Greytower demands repayment on the full cargo, as if we had sign a contrast of insurance!"
    new "The cargo was stolen, but Lord Greytower demands repayment on the full cargo, as if we had sign a contrast of insurance!"

    old "But we only ever offered to transport his goods, not bear all risk. We would never have agreed to such a thing."
    new "But we only ever offered to transport his goods, not bear all risk. We would never have agreed to such a thing."

    old "Well, you took money on his contract to transport the goods. Having failed to transport them, at the very least, you owe this much back to him?"
    new "Well, you took money on his contract to transport the goods. Having failed to transport them, at the very least, you owe this much back to him?"

    old "The merchant nodded again."
    new "The merchant nodded again."

    old "Yes, your Highness, but Lord Greytower will see no reason in the mattter!"
    new "Yes, your Highness, but Lord Greytower will see no reason in the mattter!"

    old "He says that if his men see us, they should take everything from us until the debt it settled."
    new "He says that if his men see us, they should take everything from us until the debt it settled."

    old "Even if I wanted to repay him, I cannot continue my business, for as soon as I arrive back in the North, I risk attack from both bandits and armsmen."
    new "Even if I wanted to repay him, I cannot continue my business, for as soon as I arrive back in the North, I risk attack from both bandits and armsmen."

    old "Very well, and this is all?"
    new "Very well, and this is all?"

    old "The man looked down, seemingly anxious."
    new "The man looked down, seemingly anxious."

    old "Speak or be silent, I will not have you act in between."
    new "Speak or be silent, I will not have you act in between."

    old "The man raised his head and clear his throat."
    new "The man raised his head and clear his throat."

    old "There is one more matter...but I fear to even speak it, invites disaster...yet it is the truth!"
    new "There is one more matter...but I fear to even speak it, invites disaster...yet it is the truth!"

    old "Then speak to the matter."
    new "Then speak to the matter."

    old "When we were attacked by the bandits...during the fight, one of the bandits was struck across the face by one of ours guards, before the guard was slain."
    new "When we were attacked by the bandits...during the fight, one of the bandits was struck across the face by one of ours guards, before the guard was slain."

    old "Well...in the days after we had to flee from the North, but I received news from one of my friends that still lives there..."
    new "Well...in the days after we had to flee from the North, but I received news from one of my friends that still lives there..."

    old "He had heard of my story and he told me that..."
    new "He had heard of my story and he told me that..."

    old "The man paused."
    new "The man paused."

    old "Gathering his courage, the decided to continue."
    new "Gathering his courage, the decided to continue."

    old "He told me that not long after my attack, Lord Greytower's son, Oliver Greytower, was seen returning to his father's home..."
    new "He told me that not long after my attack, Lord Greytower's son, Oliver Greytower, was seen returning to his father's home..."

    old "Bearing now a new and fresh scar, across his face..."
    new "Bearing now a new and fresh scar, across his face..."

    old "She looked at Kravel, who gestured that he had heard the same story."
    new "She looked at Kravel, who gestured that he had heard the same story."

    old "Have you heard anything of this?"
    new "Have you heard anything of this?"

    old "Her Spymaster nodded."
    new "Her Spymaster nodded."

    old "There have been rumors to the fact yes. A hunting accident, I believe his father said."
    new "There have been rumors to the fact yes. A hunting accident, I believe his father said."

    old "Sarah began to consider all the facts."
    new "Sarah began to consider all the facts."

    old "You understand what you are saying, correct?"
    new "You understand what you are saying, correct?"

    old "The merchant nodded, frightened."
    new "The merchant nodded, frightened."

    old "I feared to speak of it, were it not the truth."
    new "I feared to speak of it, were it not the truth."

    old "Sarah leaned back."
    new "Sarah leaned back."

    old "You accuse Lord Greytower's son, perhaps indirectly even himself, of engaging in banditry."
    new "You accuse Lord Greytower's son, perhaps indirectly even himself, of engaging in banditry."

    old "His eldest son and heir, Oliver."
    new "His eldest son and heir, Oliver."

    old "The punishment for such an offence would be grave."
    new "The punishment for such an offence would be grave."

    old "The merchant only nodded, fearing to speak much more."
    new "The merchant only nodded, fearing to speak much more."

    old "The Greytower family was not particularly important in the whole of Rosanna."
    new "The Greytower family was not particularly important in the whole of Rosanna."

    old "They were a family in the North, but only one of many and far from the most important."
    new "They were a family in the North, but only one of many and far from the most important."

    old "They were certainly not a great house."
    new "They were certainly not a great house."

    old "During Marion's rebellion, they had pledged loyalty to her House, and had even send forth soldiers to help put the rebellion down."
    new "During Marion's rebellion, they had pledged loyalty to her House, and had even send forth soldiers to help put the rebellion down."

    old "They had been loyal."
    new "They had been loyal."

    old "But could loyalty excuse possible banditry?"
    new "But could loyalty excuse possible banditry?"

    old "Sarah couldn't be too surprised. Much of the wealth that had come to Rosanna in recent years had been focussed around the Capital and the Southern provinces, near the sea."
    new "Sarah couldn't be too surprised. Much of the wealth that had come to Rosanna in recent years had been focussed around the Capital and the Southern provinces, near the sea."

    old "The Northern provinces had made clear that they felt left out of the growing economy."
    new "The Northern provinces had made clear that they felt left out of the growing economy."

    old "Perhaps, some even so desperate as to fall down to common criminality."
    new "Perhaps, some even so desperate as to fall down to common criminality."

    old "Still, did she even really know if this was the case?"
    new "Still, did she even really know if this was the case?"

    old "Perhaps Oliver had truly gotten wounded in a hunting accident, strange of a coincidence as it might be."
    new "Perhaps Oliver had truly gotten wounded in a hunting accident, strange of a coincidence as it might be."

    old "Could she really condemn a man and his family on just this man's word?"
    new "Could she really condemn a man and his family on just this man's word?"

    old "Find in favor of House Greytower"
    new "Find in favor of House Greytower"

    old "The matter was a small dispute."
    new "The matter was a small dispute."

    old "Even if what the man said was true, it was too trivial for her to risk upsetting an otherwise loyal house."
    new "Even if what the man said was true, it was too trivial for her to risk upsetting an otherwise loyal house."

    old "Besides, the Greytowers would hardly be the first royal house to commit banditry and given a pass."
    new "Besides, the Greytowers would hardly be the first royal house to commit banditry and given a pass."

    old "I have heard enough."
    new "I have heard enough."

    old "You have offered us little real evidence, more than a piece of paper whose contents House Greytower no doubt disputes."
    new "You have offered us little real evidence, more than a piece of paper whose contents House Greytower no doubt disputes."

    old "You took on a contract to deliver cargo, and have failed to do so."
    new "You took on a contract to deliver cargo, and have failed to do so."

    old "You must make House Greytower whole again."
    new "You must make House Greytower whole again."

    old "Either in money or sufficient product to match what was lost."
    new "Either in money or sufficient product to match what was lost."

    old "It is Lord Greytower's right to collect on this debts, and should you pass in his domain, he may do as he sees fit to extract it from you."
    new "It is Lord Greytower's right to collect on this debts, and should you pass in his domain, he may do as he sees fit to extract it from you."

    old "She saw the merchant's face drop."
    new "She saw the merchant's face drop."

    old "This...this will ruin me! I don't have that kind of money, I can't-"
    new "This...this will ruin me! I don't have that kind of money, I can't-"

    old "Sarah raised one hand."
    new "Sarah raised one hand."

    old "You came for a ruling I have given you one. Pleading with me more will not invite reconsideration, only my annoyance."
    new "You came for a ruling I have given you one. Pleading with me more will not invite reconsideration, only my annoyance."

    old "I suggest you avoid speaking more to the matter."
    new "I suggest you avoid speaking more to the matter."

    old "The merchant, his face now white as paper, turned and stumbled out the room."
    new "The merchant, his face now white as paper, turned and stumbled out the room."

    old "Find in favor of the Merchant"
    new "Find in favor of the Merchant"

    old "The matter might be small, but it was one of fundamental rules."
    new "The matter might be small, but it was one of fundamental rules."

    old "Either Rosanna respected the law, or it did not."
    new "Either Rosanna respected the law, or it did not."

    old "Your case is compelling and I find your contract to be clear, and believe it to be genuine."
    new "Your case is compelling and I find your contract to be clear, and believe it to be genuine."

    old "I shall have the Court author a write, stating that you owe House Greytower only repayment on the transport fee, not the entire cargo."
    new "I shall have the Court author a write, stating that you owe House Greytower only repayment on the transport fee, not the entire cargo."

    old "Deliver that writ to House Greytower, and they will obey my verdict."
    new "Deliver that writ to House Greytower, and they will obey my verdict."

    old "The merchant bowed his head low."
    new "The merchant bowed his head low."

    old "Thank you, your Highness, you have saved my business!"
    new "Thank you, your Highness, you have saved my business!"

    old "Go, you can collect the writ later today."
    new "Go, you can collect the writ later today."

    old "The merchant bowed his head as he slowly backed out of the room, continuing to speak thanks."
    new "The merchant bowed his head as he slowly backed out of the room, continuing to speak thanks."

    old "Condemn Oliver to death"
    new "Condemn Oliver to death"

    old "Hers was a kingdom of rules and laws."
    new "Hers was a kingdom of rules and laws."

    old "For anyone to commit banditry was bad enough, but for a Lord to have it be done under the protection of the Crown, untolerable."
    new "For anyone to commit banditry was bad enough, but for a Lord to have it be done under the protection of the Crown, untolerable."

    old "Such a thing could undermine everything she had done to build trust in Rosanna's institutions."
    new "Such a thing could undermine everything she had done to build trust in Rosanna's institutions."

    old "House Greytower was loyal, but they were not above her laws. Nobody was."
    new "House Greytower was loyal, but they were not above her laws. Nobody was."

    old "You have spoken and I have heard."
    new "You have spoken and I have heard."

    old "Lord Greytower's son, Oliver Greytower, has enacted a crime of gross criminality."
    new "Lord Greytower's son, Oliver Greytower, has enacted a crime of gross criminality."

    old "The guilt of which is marked on his face by a blade."
    new "The guilt of which is marked on his face by a blade."

    old "Sarah turned towards one of the knights."
    new "Sarah turned towards one of the knights."

    old "Gather up some men and go forth into the Northern provinces."
    new "Gather up some men and go forth into the Northern provinces."

    old "Ride out to Lord Greytower's mansion and arrest his son Oliver."
    new "Ride out to Lord Greytower's mansion and arrest his son Oliver."

    old "Deliver him back to me in chains and I shall pass the sentence myself."
    new "Deliver him back to me in chains and I shall pass the sentence myself."

    old "Sarah paused for a moment."
    new "Sarah paused for a moment."

    old "Should he fail to obey my order to appear before this Court, you have my permission to do anything to compel him."
    new "Should he fail to obey my order to appear before this Court, you have my permission to do anything to compel him."

    old "She did not say it expressly, but it was clear to everyone."
    new "She did not say it expressly, but it was clear to everyone."

    old "Death."
    new "Death."

    old "If Oliver would refuse to come, or could not be forced to, they were meant to slay him."
    new "If Oliver would refuse to come, or could not be forced to, they were meant to slay him."

    old "At her word, the knights gathered and set out."
    new "At her word, the knights gathered and set out."

    old "The merchant, for his part, thanked her and left, still rattled by quite how far reaching her verdict had been."
    new "The merchant, for his part, thanked her and left, still rattled by quite how far reaching her verdict had been."

    old "From the corner of her eyes, she saw Spymaster Kravel look at her."
    new "From the corner of her eyes, she saw Spymaster Kravel look at her."

    old "Sarah leaned back into her throne, idly passing some documents between her hands."
    new "Sarah leaned back into her throne, idly passing some documents between her hands."

    old "She saw Kravel still looking at her."
    new "She saw Kravel still looking at her."

    old "There is nothing quite as annoying as a man who wishes to speak but holds his tongue."
    new "There is nothing quite as annoying as a man who wishes to speak but holds his tongue."

    old "Make up your mind and speak or be done about it."
    new "Make up your mind and speak or be done about it."

    old "She saw Kravel take a few steps up the stairs to the throne."
    new "She saw Kravel take a few steps up the stairs to the throne."

    old "Your Grace, was it truly wise to come down so hard on Oliver Greytower?"
    new "Your Grace, was it truly wise to come down so hard on Oliver Greytower?"

    old "Why? Must we let every small noble house rule their land like tyrants?"
    new "Why? Must we let every small noble house rule their land like tyrants?"

    old "Of course not, but the evidence..."
    new "Of course not, but the evidence..."

    old "He bears a scar on his face, does he not?"
    new "He bears a scar on his face, does he not?"

    old "A hunting accident, so his father says..."
    new "A hunting accident, so his father says..."

    old "Sarah scoffed."
    new "Sarah scoffed."

    old "Hunting accident?"
    new "Hunting accident?"

    old "Was he trying to headbutt a boar?"
    new "Was he trying to headbutt a boar?"

    old "Sarah could see Kravel equally doubted such an explanation."
    new "Sarah could see Kravel equally doubted such an explanation."

    old "Still...his father will not appreciate this. His house was loyal during the rebellion."
    new "Still...his father will not appreciate this. His house was loyal during the rebellion."

    old "Yes, I am well aware of who was and who was not loyal to me in those times."
    new "Yes, I am well aware of who was and who was not loyal to me in those times."

    old "But you and everyone else seems to forget why they were loyal."
    new "But you and everyone else seems to forget why they were loyal."

    old "They were not loyal because they stood to make money from it. They were loyal because their oathsworn duty commanded it."
    new "They were not loyal because they stood to make money from it. They were loyal because their oathsworn duty commanded it."

    old "Sarah sighed and leaned onto the side of the throne."
    new "Sarah sighed and leaned onto the side of the throne."

    old "Every single imbecile in this nation demands some kind of compensation or reward for things they were supposed to do."
    new "Every single imbecile in this nation demands some kind of compensation or reward for things they were supposed to do."

    old "They are as weak husbands, demanding a reward because they were faithful to their wives."
    new "They are as weak husbands, demanding a reward because they were faithful to their wives."

    old "When did a vow or an oath become a means to extract a concession?"
    new "When did a vow or an oath become a means to extract a concession?"

    old "When did men begin to believe their honour to be a currency, exchanged for material gain as if they were in a common bazaar?"
    new "When did men begin to believe their honour to be a currency, exchanged for material gain as if they were in a common bazaar?"

    old "She saw Kravel shrink away."
    new "She saw Kravel shrink away."

    old "I am sorry, your Grace. I should not have spoken to the matter. I understand and trust your decision."
    new "I am sorry, your Grace. I should not have spoken to the matter. I understand and trust your decision."

    old "I am sorry, Kravel."
    new "I am sorry, Kravel."

    old "The day has been long and I lost my temper with you. You only sought to give counsel. I apologize."
    new "The day has been long and I lost my temper with you. You only sought to give counsel. I apologize."

    old "Her Spymaster threw up his hands."
    new "Her Spymaster threw up his hands."

    old "You owe me no apology or excuse, your Grace. I serve at your pleasure and pray only that I continue to do so."
    new "You owe me no apology or excuse, your Grace. I serve at your pleasure and pray only that I continue to do so."

    old "Sarah stood up from the throne and looked across the room."
    new "Sarah stood up from the throne and looked across the room."

    old "Well, if this settles all standing matters before the Court, let us then-"
    new "Well, if this settles all standing matters before the Court, let us then-"

    old "A man walked in through the door to the Great Hall."
    new "A man walked in through the door to the Great Hall."

    old "A royal messenger from Normandi, comes bearing a missive!"
    new "A royal messenger from Normandi, comes bearing a missive!"

    old "Sarah fell back in her throne."
    new "Sarah fell back in her throne."

    old "She would have been annoyed, had it not been for the nature of the arriving man."
    new "She would have been annoyed, had it not been for the nature of the arriving man."

    old "A royal messenger."
    new "A royal messenger."

    old "From Normandi, one of the neighbouring kingdoms to Rosanna, a member of the Union Kingdoms."
    new "From Normandi, one of the neighbouring kingdoms to Rosanna, a member of the Union Kingdoms."

    old "Your Grace!"
    new "Your Grace!"

    old "I have ridden long and hard from the nation of Normandi, bearing a message to you from Queen Maeiv."
    new "I have ridden long and hard from the nation of Normandi, bearing a message to you from Queen Maeiv."

    old "Queen Maeiv, the Silent-Queen. Ruler of Normandi for decades now."
    new "Queen Maeiv, the Silent-Queen. Ruler of Normandi for decades now."

    old "She had come to power years before Sarah's father had died."
    new "She had come to power years before Sarah's father had died."

    old "Sarah could remember her rise, even though she herself had been quite young at the time."
    new "Sarah could remember her rise, even though she herself had been quite young at the time."

    old "The former king of Normandi had enjoyed life quite excessively."
    new "The former king of Normandi had enjoyed life quite excessively."

    old "Taking drink and food with great abundance. But above all, he enjoyed women."
    new "Taking drink and food with great abundance. But above all, he enjoyed women."

    old "And just as the drink and food left their mark on him, so too did his frequent philandering."
    new "And just as the drink and food left their mark on him, so too did his frequent philandering."

    old "By the time he died, there were supposedly as many as thirty children, of varying stature and claim to the throne."
    new "By the time he died, there were supposedly as many as thirty children, of varying stature and claim to the throne."

    old "When the various noble houses all sided with different royal born and bastard born children, few suspected the young Maeiv to be much of a contender."
    new "When the various noble houses all sided with different royal born and bastard born children, few suspected the young Maeiv to be much of a contender."

    old "Young, inexperienced and a woman, she was not a serious claimant."
    new "Young, inexperienced and a woman, she was not a serious claimant."

    old "But as the nation descended into infighting, it was her very unremarkable nature that quickly became her power."
    new "But as the nation descended into infighting, it was her very unremarkable nature that quickly became her power."

    old "Those with the strongest claims fought those who they imagined their most distinct rivals, those with other strong claims."
    new "Those with the strongest claims fought those who they imagined their most distinct rivals, those with other strong claims."

    old "And as one took out the other, Maeiv simply sat on the sideline and waited."
    new "And as one took out the other, Maeiv simply sat on the sideline and waited."

    old "One by one, they tired out their armies and their wealth, and before long, Maeiv stood unmolested, with one of the few remaining armies and hoards."
    new "One by one, they tired out their armies and their wealth, and before long, Maeiv stood unmolested, with one of the few remaining armies and hoards."

    old "When she finally began to make her move, only five serious contenders remained."
    new "When she finally began to make her move, only five serious contenders remained."

    old "Each had fought so feverishly for the crown, that by now, each had inflicted countless offenses to the other houses."
    new "Each had fought so feverishly for the crown, that by now, each had inflicted countless offenses to the other houses."

    old "Every claimant could draft a list of brutalities they stood accused of and that they accused others of."
    new "Every claimant could draft a list of brutalities they stood accused of and that they accused others of."

    old "Everyone, except distant Maeiv."
    new "Everyone, except distant Maeiv."

    old "Maeiv who had offended few, and took offense from few."
    new "Maeiv who had offended few, and took offense from few."

    old "Maeiv whose armies still stood solid and whose wealth had only grown where others faded."
    new "Maeiv whose armies still stood solid and whose wealth had only grown where others faded."

    old "In the end, no single House could break another. Each too weak to defeat the others, each too strong to be defeated."
    new "In the end, no single House could break another. Each too weak to defeat the others, each too strong to be defeated."

    old "When the time came to make a peace and crown an heir, none could agree."
    new "When the time came to make a peace and crown an heir, none could agree."

    old "There was too much pain among them. Too much history that was still recent."
    new "There was too much pain among them. Too much history that was still recent."

    old "All, except silent-Maeiv, who only smiled and had brutalized nobody."
    new "All, except silent-Maeiv, who only smiled and had brutalized nobody."

    old "And in the end, Maeiv proved the only one who all the others could find agreeable."
    new "And in the end, Maeiv proved the only one who all the others could find agreeable."

    old "In the 'War of Rivers', as it later came to be called, the crown ended up falling towards not the richest, not the most violent or even the strongest."
    new "In the 'War of Rivers', as it later came to be called, the crown ended up falling towards not the richest, not the most violent or even the strongest."

    old "And so, Queen Maeiv won both her crown and her moniker. The Silent-Queen."
    new "And so, Queen Maeiv won both her crown and her moniker. The Silent-Queen."

    old "Be welcome in my court."
    new "Be welcome in my court."

    old "Sarah returned her attention to the messenger."
    new "Sarah returned her attention to the messenger."

    old "Are you in need of anything?"
    new "Are you in need of anything?"

    old "Your offer is most kind, but I fear that I was tasked with delivering this message with the great of haste."
    new "Your offer is most kind, but I fear that I was tasked with delivering this message with the great of haste."

    old "I ask your forgiveness that I shall first deliver this, before I shall partake in any of your kindness."
    new "I ask your forgiveness that I shall first deliver this, before I shall partake in any of your kindness."

    old "Even most messages from other countries were rarely brought so...pressingly."
    new "Even most messages from other countries were rarely brought so...pressingly."

    old "Tell me then, what is your message?"
    new "Tell me then, what is your message?"

    old "I have sworn an oath by the Gods, my own life and the life of my family, that I would not break the seal on this letter."
